  "text": "The first examples of graphs that are not word-representable were given in [CITATION_1] . In fact, V. Limouzy [private communication, 2014] noticed that it is NP-hard to determine whether a given graph is wordrepresentable, see [CITATION_2] for the details. In [CITATION_3] it was proved that any comparability graph G is not just word-representable, but it is permutationally word-representable. That is, for the graph G, there exists a word w with the necessary letter alternation properties such that w is obtained by concatenating a number of permutations.",
